<text>Correlation functions


For simulations that involve many particles, the produced data can seem quite stochastic, unless they are refined. Correlation functions represent a refinement method to quantitate the extent one property is related to another.

Suppose we have two data sets ( x1 , x2 , ......, xN ) and ( y1 , y2 , ......, yN ) (e.g. two time series of dynamical evolution), the following function depicts how much they are correlated to each other: 

 


Note that cxx=cyy=1 , cx,-x=cy,-y=-1. This means when the absolute value of the correlation function equals to unity, the two sets are most strongly correlated---This is obvious: they are either identical to each other, or mirror-symmetric to each other. Except for these two extremes, the absolute value of a correlation function are normally less than one. The smaller it is, the weaker the correlation it describes is. It should be pointed out that the creditability of the correlation function decreases when the number of data points N decreases.

See time correlation functions.

 
